"1326–1344":"1326–1344","1343–1388":"1343–1388","1344–Female":"1344–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1326–1352":"1326–1352","14 août 1352":"14 augustus 1352","1326":"1326","1344":"1344","1388":"1388","1343":"1343","Aft 1344":"na 1344","1352":"1352","23 MAY 1342":"23 mei 1342","Saint-Crépin-aux-Bois, , Picardie, France":"Saint-Crépin-aux-Bois, Oise, Picardie, Frankrijk","Somme, Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Somme, Cher, Centre, Frankrijk","Nesle, Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France":"Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Frankrijk","Saint Crepin Aux Bois, Picardie, France":"Saint-Crépin-aux-Bois, Oise, Picardie, Frankrijk","Nesle-l'Hôpital, Somme, Picardie, France":"Nesle-l'Hôpital, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1326–14 août 1352":"1326–14 August 1352","1326–1344":"1326–1344","1343–1388":"1343–1388","1344–Female":"1344–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1326–1352":"1326–1352","14 août 1352":"14 August 1352","1326":"1326","1344":"1344","1388":"1388","1343":"1343","Aft 1344":"after 1344","1352":"1352","23 MAY 1342":"23 May 1342","Saint-Crépin-aux-Bois, , Picardie, France":"Saint-Crépin-aux-Bois, Oise, Picardie, France","Somme, Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Somme, Cher, Centre, France","Nesle, Péronne, Somme, Picardie, France":"Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Saint Crepin Aux Bois, Picardie, France":"Saint-Crépin-aux-Bois, Oise, Picardie, France","Nesle-l'Hôpital, Somme, Picardie, France":"Nesle-l'Hôpital, Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Nesle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["South German and Swiss German:","variant of   Nestel  .","from a diminutive of   Nast  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nestel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Wolfram.  Jewish Aron, Hyman.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): metonymic occupational name for a ribbon and cord maker, from Middle High German <i>nestel</i> ‘(shoe)lace, drawstring, cord’."]}]},{"name":"Mello","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Adelino, Ana, Joaquin, Acacio, Claudio, Cristina, Fernando, Americo, Enrique.  Portuguese Duarte, Joaquim, Armanda, Joao, Paulo, Serafim.","Italian: probably from a short form of a personal name ending with the hypocoristic suffix <i>-ello</i>, such as <i>Giacomello</i> from   Giacomo  .","Portuguese: variant of   Melo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Giacomo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Domenico, Gino, Salvatore.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Giacomo</i>, from Latin <i>Jacobus</i> via Late Latin <i>Jacomus</i> (see   James   and   Jacob  )."]},{"name":"Melle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Heinz, Horst, Kurt, Otto.","Italian: habitational name from Melle in Cuneo province (Piedmont); in some cases possibly also a variant of a personal name such as   Mello   1.","Norwegian: probably a variant of   Mele  ."]},{"name":"Mellone","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Emidio, Luigi, Pasquale.","Italian: from an augmentative of   Mello  ."]}]},{"name":"Baron","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the title of nobility, along the lines of   Earl   and   Duke .  The title arose in the Norman feudal system and seems to be of Germanic origin, derived from Old English <i>beorn</i> ‘young warrior’ or a related continental Germanic form. In part the given name, and in particular the variant  <b>Barron</b> , may represent the surname derived from the title."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Guy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of a compound name starting with <i>witu</i> ‘wood’ or <i>wīt</i> ‘wide’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England. In Old French initial <i>w-</i> regularly became <i>gu-</i>. The usual Norman forms of the name were <i>Gy</i> or <i>Guido</i>. In medieval Latin the same name is found as <i>Wido</i>. It was a popular name among the Normans, enhanced no doubt by the romance of Guy of Warwick, recounting the exploits of a folk hero of the Crusades."],"variants":[]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Vivian   and   Vivien ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Baron Guy IV Nesle Mello d'Offemont was born in 1326, in Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France. He married Lady Jeanne de Bruyères on 23 May 1342, in Saint-Crépin-aux-Bois, Oise, Picardie, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died on 14 August 1352, in Somme, Cher, Centre, France, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1326–14 août 1352":"1326–14. august 1352","1326–1344":"1326–1344","1343–1388":"1343–1388","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","–Female":"Surnu